{
  "doc_id": "9670",
  "text": "Reduced Nodal signaling gives rise to several abnormalities in addition to holoprosencephaly and anterior head truncation, including randomized left-right patterning and hyposplenia [CITATION_1] ). Left-right patterning malformations have also been observed in mice carrying a targeted deletion of Growth and Differentiation Factor 1 (GDF-1), another member of the TGF-β superfamily, which was explained by the observation that GDF-1 signaling is required for expression of Nodal in the lateral plate mesoderm [CITATION_2] . Nodal expression is controlled by two distinct regulatory elements, one upstream enhancer that regulates expression in the node, and one intronic enhancer that regulates expression in the epiblast, visceral endoderm, and lateral plate mesoderm [CITATION_3] . Since GDF-1 is crucial for expression of Nodal in the lateral plate mesoderm, it may also affect other expression domains of Nodal that are regulated by the intronic enhancer. A complex consisting of phosphorylated Smad 2 or 3 and the transcription factor Foxh1 can bind to the intronic enhancer, thereby establishing a positive feedback loop controlling Nodal gene expression [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . GDF-1 has been shown to utilize similar receptors as Nodal, including ALK4, Cripto and ActRIIA or ActRIIB [CITATION_6] . Thus, GDF-1 may synergize with Nodal by at least two -not mutually exclusive -mechanisms, namely reinforcing Nodal expression and activating a similar set of receptors and Smad proteins.",
